                        "username": "geissonator"
                    },
                    "message": "Is there some help text for this? I wasn't on the initial reviews so I don't even know what a \"sink\" is :) \n\nAlso, is this an API change? Requiring a new parameter. Could we just default to whatever was used before if not input?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "main.c",
                    "line": 105,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Jeffery",
                        "email": "andrew@aj.id.au",
                        "username": "amboar"
                    },
                    "message": "> Is there some help text for this? I wasn't on the initial reviews so I don't even know what a \"sink\" is :) \n\nI'll add some comments. In a conceptual sense the application takes an input event (from a source) and translates that into an output event (on a sink). A sink implementation describes the actions that will be taken in response to an input event. A source implementation describes how to listen for an input event. The set of input events are currently defined as the ASCII values for 'D' (debug) and 'R' (reboot).\n\n> Also, is this an API change? Requiring a new parameter. Could we just default to whatever was used before if not input?\n\nThis isn't an API (or command-line interface) change. It's still an option flag, not an argument on the command line, however the option itself requires an argument if it is specified. Valid invocations look like:\n\n 1. $ debug-trigger\n 2. $ debug-trigger --sink=sysrq .../serio_raw0\n\nThe \"required_argument\" in this case is 'sysrq', the option is --sink.\n\nThe defaults remain as they were before this patch."
                },
                {
                    "file": "main.c",
                    "line": 105,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Jeffery",
                        "email": "andrew@aj.id.au",
                        "username": "amboar"
                    },
                    "message": "Done"
                },
                {
                    "file": "main.c",
                    "line": 143,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Geissler",
                        "email": "andrew@geissonator.com",
                        "username": "geissonator"
                    },
                    "message": "I'm struggling with this logic a bit. If sink_name is not \"sysrq\" then we never open the device and sinkfd never gets set...but we still go and use it down on line 151 with it's default?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "main.c",
                    "line": 143,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Jeffery",
                        "email": "andrew@aj.id.au",
                        "username": "amboar"
                    },
                    "message": "I'll add some comments. Basically, implement the original behaviour, but also give a name to the original sink implementation (called 'sysrq'). So, if:\n\n1. --sink isn't specified on the commandline, or\n2. --sink=sysrq is specified on the commandline\n\nthen the sink is the sysrq sink."
                },
                {
